item.title: Mahmoud Khalil deportation case: Federal judge orders release of Palestinian activist; govt given till Friday to appeal
item.description: A federal judge ordered the release of Mahmoud Khalil, a legal US resident detained after participating in pro-Palestinian demonstrations. The judge cited irreparable harm to Khalil's career and free speech rights due to his detention. Despite the ruling, Khalil will remain in custody pending a possible government appeal, highlighting ongoing legal battles over activism and immigration.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Cannot have nuclear weapons’: Donald Trump vows to stop Iran; US orders partial Iraq embassy evacuation
item.description: Amid rising tensions and a partial US embassy evacuation in Iraq, Donald Trump has firmly stated that the United States will prevent Iran from acquiring nuclear weapons. Diplomatic efforts to revive the nuclear deal face hurdles, particularly regarding uranium enrichment.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Ballymena riots: Fires rage as protests over alleged assault fuel anti-immigrant unrest in Northern Ireland
item.description: Violent riots have erupted in Northern Ireland, injuring over 30 police officers after two 14-year-old boys were charged with attempted sexual assault. Triggered by anti-immigrant sentiment and fueled by far-right social media, the unrest spread from Ballymena to Belfast and other towns.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: French doctor claims that Greta Thunberg was mistreated by Israeli forces during Gaza aid mission
item.description: A French doctor alleges mistreatment by Israeli authorities towards passengers, including Greta Thunberg, after their aid boat to Gaza was intercepted. Dr. André reported mockery, sleep deprivation, and limited resources. Thunberg condemned the detention as a rights violation, while Israel dismissed the voyage as a stunt, defending its blockade.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: What is Emiratisation? The UAE’s push to move over half of insurance sector jobs in Emirati hands by 2030
item.description: Emiratisation—the UAE’s initiative to increase Emirati employment, is advancing rapidly in the insurance sector, where nationals now make up 22% of employees. Minister Mohamed Al Husaini announced a new goal of 50–60% localisation by 2030, signaling a decisive effort to shift workforce demographics and strengthen national participation in a sector traditionally dominated by expatriates.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: LA protests: Over 20 arrested as tensions persist amid Trump immigration raids
item.description: Los Angeles faced curfew and protests against President Trump's immigration policies, leading to multiple arrests and clashes. Demonstrations spread nationwide, prompting National Guard deployment and legal challenges against federal actions. Tensions escalated between state and federal authorities, with concerns over military involvement in immigration enforcement and its impact on communities.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Why US is pulling staff from the Middle East as nuclear talks with Iran stall
item.description: Amid rising tensions and stalled nuclear negotiations, the U.S. is reducing its diplomatic and military presence in the Middle East. The State Department ordered nonessential staff to depart from Baghdad and authorized optional departures from Bahrain and Kuwait. The military is also allowing voluntary departures of dependents as regional instability looms and the IAEA considers censuring Iran.

item.title: Immigration protests: Trump won't allow 'mob rule in America,' says White House
item.description: Amidst escalating protests against President Trump's immigration policies, the White House vows to restore order, denouncing demonstrators as “insurrectionists.” Following ICE raids in Los Angeles, violence erupted, prompting military intervention and criticism from California's Democratic leaders. Trump pledges to “liberate” the city, while his administration accuses local officials of failing to protect citizens and fueling unrest.

item.title: 'I could have been a flutist': Trump says he was once labelled 'brilliant at music'
item.description: Donald Trump revealed that an aptitude test as a child identified him as a musical prodigy, a revelation his father didn't embrace. Trump recalled his ability to recognize and recall musical notes with ease. He also mentioned briefly playing the flute with an instructor, though he admitted it wasn't a passion.

item.title: Trump’s immigration crackdown: LA police imposes curfew, deploys force amid protests; 197 arrested
item.description: Los Angeles is grappling with intense protests against President Trump's immigration policies, leading to a city-wide curfew and nearly 200 arrests. Mayor Karen Bass declared a local emergency due to looting and vandalism. Governor Gavin Newsom criticized Trump's 'military dragnet,' while Trump defended troop deployment, threatening to invoke the Insurrection Act.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Please do not go to airport’: Silver Airways ceases operations immediately
item.description: Silver Airways abruptly ceased operations on June 11, 2025, leaving passengers stranded after a failed bankruptcy restructuring. A deal to sell assets fell through, leading to flight cancellations across Florida, the Bahamas, and the Caribbean. Customers are advised to seek refunds through credit card companies, marking the end of the regional carrier.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Close call: Civilian plane narrowly escapes Houthi missile intercepted mid-air - Video
item.description: A Houthi ballistic missile, aimed at Israeli civilians, was intercepted by Israeli air defenses, narrowly avoiding a collision with a civilian plane. The attack, claimed by the Iran-backed Houthis, triggered sirens across central Israel and the West Bank. In response, the Israeli Navy conducted its first strike on Yemen, targeting infrastructure at the Hodeida port.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Donald Trump’s Los Angeles playbook: Chaos, crackdown - and a political win
item.description: Donald Trump deployed troops in Los Angeles due to immigration protests. This action sparked legal challenges from California Governor Gavin Newsom. Protests spread to other cities. Trump defended the move, citing a need for order. Newsom accused Trump of abusing power. The situation provides political opportunities for both Trump and Newsom.
